function findLeastNumOfUniqueInts(arr, k) {
    let freqMap = {};
    for (let n of arr) {
        freqMap[n] = (freqMap[n] || 0) + 1;
    }

    let minHeap = Object.values(freqMap).sort((a, b) => a - b);

    while (k > 0) {
        k -= minHeap.shift();
    }

    return k === 0 ? minHeap.length : minHeap.length + 1;
}
```

    The algorithm works as follows:
1. Create a frequency map for the given array of integers. This is a map where keys are the integers in the array and values are their frequency counts.
2. Create a min-heap (priority queue) from the frequency map's values.
3. While k (the number of elements to remove) is greater than 0, keep popping elements from the min-heap (which will be the one with the least frequency) and decrement the value of k by that frequency. This step simulates removing k elements.
4. If k turns out to be zero, return the size of the min-heap as the least number of unique integers. If k becomes negative (i.e., k != 0), return the size of the min-heap plus 1 as the answer.

The algorithm has a time complexity of O(n + mlogm), where n is the size of the input array, and m is the number of unique integers in it. The space complexity is also O(m) due to the frequency map and the min-heap.

